node.text:
Nile cruise Day 2 with @nourelnil ⛵️ ⁣
⁣
El Kab, on the East bank of the Nile, was once the capital of Upper Egypt and is still home to the temple of Nekhbet, as well as a row of fascinating decorated tombs carved into the slope of the mountains. We walked through a small fisherman village to get to El Kab. ⁣
⁣
In the afternoon, we visited Edfu, home to the Greco-Roman temple dedicated to the god Horus. This is among the best preserved of all Egyptian temples 🇪🇬 ⁣
⁣
⁣
🎥 by the best: @jeremybrookover⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

node.text:
Nile cruise Day 1 with @nourelnil ⛵️ ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
We visited Esna, 33 miles south of Luxor. Esna is best known for the small ancient Temple of Khnum, 9 meters below street level. It was preserved so well because most of it was buried when discovered. We walked through the temple and strolled through streets filled with markets. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
We are on the Adelaïde boat, one of the best in the Nour El Nil fleet. There are ten rooms, two suites, a staff of fifteen, a large salon, and an expansive deck. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
🎥 @jeremybrookover

There are multiple tombs of kings from different generations here which is why the area is referred to as “The Valley of the Kings.” Egypt is such a surreal place and I’m always blown away and feel drawn to something higher than myself when exploring the culture and practices of different countries, especially these ancient ones in Egypt.
